Star-args collects any extra positional arguments into a tuple named args. Double-star-kwargs collects any extra keyword arguments into a dict named kwargs.

The names args and kwargs are convention — what matters is the star and the double-star. You can rename them if it reads better in context.

At the call site, the same star and double-star are used to unpack an existing iterable or dict into the parameter list.

In code, picture def show-call taking a label, then star-args, then double-star-kwargs. Body prints the label, the args tuple, and the kwargs dict. Call it three ways — with extra positional, with mixed positional and keyword, with keyword only. Each prints the corresponding tuples and dicts.

Unpacking at the call site. Def add taking a, b, c. Bind nums to a list of one, two, three. Add of star-nums passes the list as three positional arguments — returns six. Bind config to a dict mapping a, b, c to integers. Add of double-star-config passes the dict as three keyword arguments — returns the sum.

Positional-only forward-slash and keyword-only star.

Two markers that constrain how parameters can be passed.

Forward-slash — every parameter before the slash is positional-only. Callers cannot pass them by name. Star — every parameter after the star is keyword-only. Callers must pass them by name.

You use these to lock down an application programming interface. Keyword-only for rare configuration flags, forcing callers to spell out ssl equals true rather than passing a bare true. Positional-only for parameters whose names are implementation details you do not want to commit to.

In code, picture def connect taking host, port, forward-slash, user, star, ssl with default false, timeout with default thirty. Host and port are positional-only. Ssl and timeout are keyword-only. Allowed — connect of db, fifty four thirty-two, ganesh. Connect of the same plus ssl equals true. Connect of the same with user as keyword and timeout sixty. Not allowed — passing host as a keyword, or passing ssl positionally.
